<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06304157 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06304157 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FARM; AGRICULTURE; EQUIPMENT; BUSINESS; COMPANY; EARNINGS; DECREASE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Tenneco Inc. said it lost $693 million in the third quarter, a record loss thecompany attributed mostly to continuing problems with its farm and equipmentbusiness.;   The loss amounted to $5.69 per share, compared with net income of$91 million, or 70 cents per share, for the same July-September period in1990. The loss came on revenues of $3.18 billion, compared with revenues of$3.39 billion in the same period last year.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TENNECO SUFFERS LOSS IN FARMING BUSINESS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Houston-based Tenneco said the loss included a $504 million restructuringcharge. Of that amount, $413 million was for the restructuring of the J.I.Case farm and equipment business.;   Case's restructuring will include plantclosings and additional layoffs, Tenneco spokeswoman Christine LeLaurin said.About 5,000 Case employees already have been laid off this year, reducing thecompany's worldwide workforce to about 25,600.;   &quot;There will be additionalcuts, but we're just not saying yet where or whose jobs will be affected,&quot; shesaid.;   Case, which has blamed its troubles on the recession, has 24 plantsin North America, Europe, Brazil and Australia.;   LeLaurin said Tenneco'sthird-quarter loss was a record for the company, which also is involved inshipbuilding, packaging, natural gas pipelines, automotive parts and chemicalsand minerals. Tenneco's largest previous loss was $267 million for all of1987, she said.;   For the first nine months of 1991, Tenneco lost $706million, or $5.87 per share. A year ago, the company posted net income of $431million, or $3.34 per share.;   Revenues for the first nine months were $10.02billion in 1990 and $10.63 in 1991.;   Recently, Tenneco announced plans tosell some assets, cut its dividends in half and reduce next year's capitalspending plans to improve its financial health.;   The company also announcedit was planning a $500 million stock offering to raise cash.;   The offering,which has been filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission but has notyet become effective, will be made through an underwriting syndicate managedby Morgan Stanley andamp; Co. Inc. and The First Boston Corp.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Houston  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911030  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  338  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, October 30, 199100304157,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>